<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-187-005 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 581 290</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Language  April 1991 v8 n4 p114(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Miller Freeman Publications 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>286/DOS-Extender. (from Phar Lap Software) (New and Noteworthy)(product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Phar Lap Software Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   286/DOS-Extender (Operating system enhancement) (Productintroduction)Microsoft C (Compiler) (Computer programs).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionDOS ExtendersDynamic Programming.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>286\DOS-Extender Phar Lap Software Inc. has released 286\DOS-Extender forMicrosoft C developers.andP;  It lets developers create multimegabyteprotected-mode applications for MS-DOS without changing development tools ormaking major source-code changes.andM;286\DOS-Extender works with the entire Microsoft C toolkit, providingcomplete compatibility with the Microsoft C compiler, CodeView debugger, andMicrosoft linker.andP;  It also makes extended memory available to the Microsoft Ccompiler itself.andP;  This feature lets Microsoft C users complie larger programswith full optimization and eliminates &quot;out of memory&quot; messages.andM;286\DOS-Extender supports dynamic-link libraries (DDLs), a technique fordividing large applications into smaller modules.andP;  Previously available onlyunder OS/2 and Windows, DDLs let developers create extensible applicationswith ready-made, add-in capabilities and also provide a straightforwardmethod for implementing dynamically loaded program overlays.andO;286\DOS-Extender costs $495.andM;Contact Phar Lap Software Inc., 60 Aberdeen Ave., Cambridge, Mass.andP;  02138,(617) 661-1510.andO;</TEXT></DOC>